snippet.textDisplay: Great video.  Thanks for sharing.  I’m currently researching a trip to Cape York.  I'm slowly outfitting my 80 series Landcruiser, but more as an overlander camping rig.  I don't see myself as a hardcore 4WDriver like you blokes, more of an "out of the beaten track" 4WD camping enthusiast.  I'd prefer to avoid the Old Telegraph Road for instance.  With this in mind, if I choose to take the PDR for most of the way to the Cape, do I need to do much winching?  Can I avoid steep drop-in entrances to river/creek crossings like Gunbarrell, Cannibal, Logan et al?  Maybe you can do a follow up video on the easiest and safest way to get to Cape York for overlanders like myself.  And just as you referred to, having as much fun in the cape on a $1000 Hilux.  I know I can have as much fun getting to the cape without having to tackle the most challenging routes there.  Any advise would be helpful.
snippet.textOriginal: Great video.  Thanks for sharing.  I’m currently researching a trip to Cape York.  I'm slowly outfitting my 80 series Landcruiser, but more as an overlander camping rig.  I don't see myself as a hardcore 4WDriver like you blokes, more of an "out of the beaten track" 4WD camping enthusiast.  I'd prefer to avoid the Old Telegraph Road for instance.  With this in mind, if I choose to take the PDR for most of the way to the Cape, do I need to do much winching?  Can I avoid steep drop-in entrances to river/creek crossings like Gunbarrell, Cannibal, Logan et al?  Maybe you can do a follow up video on the easiest and safest way to get to Cape York for overlanders like myself.
